data.name: ButTableSpace1.SuperTip
data.value: Formats the selection as table space. A "Table Space" should follow every table in a document. That is why this space is very small and contains the perfect amount of spacing to follow a table. Notes, Cautions, and Warning should have one "Table Space" before and one "Table Space" after the table that forms the note.

data.name: ButPageBreak.SuperTip
data.value: Toggles the page break before property of the selection. It is good practice to not use manual page breaks in documents. As a manual page break moves down a page (due to an increase in content above the page break), content below the page break becomes "uncontrolled" and floats to other pages as it pleases. Use this button instead. Whenever you select when you apply "Page Break" will ALWAYS start on a new page, without exceptions. Now your content is what we call "controlled" because you got it under control by using a combination of this Page Break button and the Keep w/Next button.

data.name: ButKeepWithNext.SuperTip
data.value: Keeps the current selection with the immediate following paragraph. Typically this should be used on a heading, or on the leader text prior to a list; figures should have this applied so that the image will "stick" to the figure caption. This way, as content wraps to a new page, the connected bits will "stick" together.

data.name: ButInsertGraphic.ScreenTip
data.value: Start a new (clean) line before using [Insert Graphic]. This button inserts a graphic placeholder, including a properly formatted figure caption (that auto counts). Neat! Now I can just write the document and then come back later to put in the graphics! Yay!

data.name: ButSnipitz.SuperTip
data.value: Snipits allows a group of collaborators to copy (or to "snip") content from a document, store the snip in an intuitive category, and then recall the content at a later time with a click! Typical document construction is repetative (Part A, Part B, Part C). Snip "Part A" and save it for the next time you write something similar (e.g. "Part A" inserted from Snipits, "Part E" new content (Snip "Part E for" later use as well!)).

data.name: ButXREF.SuperTip
data.value: XRef, the Cross-Reference Manager, allows you to work with the cross-references in your document. From inserting an auto-updating reference to Step 19, or an auto-counting table caption, to scanning a document for accurate cross-references, or updating the Table of Contents, XRef is your one stop shop!

data.name: ButTemplates.SuperTip
data.value: Templates, the Document Template Manager, allows rapid adjustment of a document's template. Switch a document from the default template to any of the stored templates in a click! The key to success is with styles. Ensure that when you create or edit a document that you are using a stylized template, and using the styles found in the "Styles" group on the NCS Ribbon.

data.name: ButUnitConverter.SuperTip
data.value: Select a single unit of measure (e.g. 2 in.) and then press the Unit Converter button to convert the selected unit of measure into the metric (if it is a standard unit of measure) or to standard (if it is a metric unit of measure). The resulting conversion would produce output with the standard unit followed by the metric unit in hard brackets (e.g. "2 in. [58.1 mm]"). Have fun with this! Many units of measure are included, and more can easily be added if needed.

data.name: ButUpdateFields.SuperTip
data.value: This is a magic button. Documents often contain many Fields which auto populate (e.g. page numbers that adjust according to the documents page count). Many fields will not "update" however, unless told to do so. This button speaks to all of the fields in your document (every one!). Common Fields found in documents include (but not limited to): Table of Contents, Header and Footer content, Page Numbers, Document Title, Document Type, Document Version, etc.)

data.name: ButToggleDocProps.SuperTip
data.value: Toggles the document panel open or close. Enter values into the Title (Title of the document), Subject (type of document (e.g. Standard Operating Procedure)), and Status (Document Version Number) fields to have the values populate throughout the document where necessary.

data.name: ButFormatNotes.SuperTip
data.value: Formats the selected table to the correct note, caution, and worning style. This button is typically used when older documents require reformatting into the newest styles. Use only on tables with 1 row and 2 columns.
